Principal Components Analysis Notes

Shelby Blythe

11/8/2021

Introduction:

For the demonstration of DESeq2, I used a built-in PCA plotting function (DESeq2::plotPCA). This is convenient for doing a quick PCA check on data after you’ve set up a DESeq object for analysis. This, however, is a very use-specific instance of doing PCA and is unnecessarily constrained. Here I have some notes on more general application of PCA to your data.

The alternative is to use the base-R PCA function prcomp. Below, I will set up the same data as for the DESeq2 demonstration and demonstrate this more general function.

This is important to cover since this isn’t necessarily just a thing you would want to do for DESeq analysis, but rather something that is useful for examining your data regardless of the downstream application.

PCA:

We have now generated the table of interest for doing PCA. In the DESeq demonstration, we generated a DESeq object and eventually used plotPCA to explore the first and second principal components. Here we will do the same but with prcomp. Note that you can check what the source code is for plotPCA with the command DESeq2:::plotPCA.DESeqTransform. The implementation below is similar to what the built-in function does, but gives us the versatility to explore additional principal components.

# first we transform the count data to log2 scale using the 'regularized log' transformation.
scaled = rlog(tubcounts, blind = TRUE)

# next we calculate the per-row variance in the transformed table.
vars = rowVars(scaled)

# then we re-order the rows so that the most variable rows are on top.
scaled = scaled[order(vars, decreasing = TRUE),]

# here we perform PCA using `prcomp`. We transpose (`t`) the matrix and only operate on the top 1000 most variable regions. I select this magnitude of 'most variant' peaks in this example because this is the order of magnitude of expected differences. Increasing the number of peaks considered yields similar results, but cuts in to the amount of variance explained by the primary principal components.
pca = prcomp(t(scaled[1:1000,]))

# we calculate the percent variance explained by each principal component by extracting these values from the summary.
percentVar = round(100 * summary(pca)$importance[2,])
cumuVar = round(100 * summary(pca)$importance[3,])

prTab = data.frame(pca$x, tcoldata)

prTab %>% 
  ggplot(aes(PC1, PC2, color = genotype, shape = sex)) +
  geom_point(size = 3, alpha = 0.5) + 
  xlab(paste0("PC1: ", percentVar[1], "% variance")) + ylab(paste0("PC2: ", percentVar[2], "% variance")) + 
  scale_color_manual(values = c("tomato", "blue")) + theme(axis.line = element_line(color = "black")) + 
  theme_bw() +  
  coord_fixed() +
  labs(title = 'Principal Component Analysis')

This is close, but not exactly identical to what we got with the DESeq approach. Note however that the sign of the principal components are meaningless.

With the output of prcomp, we can visualize the fraction of variance captured by all of the calculated principal components.

b = barplot(percentVar, horiz = FALSE, las = 1, ylab = 'Variance (%)', ylim = c(0,105))
lines(b, cumuVar, type = 'b', col = 'red')

Bars show the percent of variance captured by each principal component. The red line shows the cumulative variance.

There are statistical methods that you could apply to this distribution in order to figure out ‘how many’ principal components are worth keeping. Here, we see that two principal components account for 84% of the total variance. If we added PC3 and PC4, we would get up to 89%. What do PC3 and PC4 look like, in terms of our samples?

prTab %>% 
  ggplot(aes(PC3, PC4, color = genotype, shape = sex)) +
  geom_point(size = 3, alpha = 0.5) + 
  xlab(paste0("PC3: ", percentVar[3], "% variance")) + ylab(paste0("PC4: ", percentVar[4], "% variance")) + 
  scale_color_manual(values = c("tomato", "blue")) + theme(axis.line = element_line(color = "black")) + 
  theme_bw() +  
  coord_fixed() +
  labs(title = 'Principal Component Analysis (PC3 & 4)')

Here we see that PC3 and PC4 are not distinguishing between sex or genotype, but instead appear to create a set of seven samples on the right (PC3 < 0), and five on the left (PC3 > 0).

I have some hunches. The data were generated over two days (as encoded in the serial numbers for the samples). I did seven samples on one day and five on the other. (aside: this is the point where I go back to the chunk where I generated the object tcoldata and add a column for prepDate. I then re-run all of this to get back to this point with the new tcoldata object.)

We can test whether PC3 distinguishes samples on the basis of ‘prepDate’…

prTab %>% 
  ggplot(aes(PC3, PC4, color = prepDate)) +
  geom_point(size = 3, alpha = 0.5) + 
  xlab(paste0("PC3: ", percentVar[3], "% variance")) + ylab(paste0("PC4: ", percentVar[4], "% variance")) + 
  scale_color_manual(values = c("tomato", "blue")) + theme(axis.line = element_line(color = "black")) + 
  theme_bw() +  
  coord_fixed() +
  labs(title = 'Principal Component Analysis (PC3 & 4)')

Prep date does not explain either PC3 or PC4. I’ve looked over all the metadata for these libraries and nothing seems to explain either of these principal components.

Do we need to care about these? There are several criteria that can be applied to decide how many principal components to retain. One is the “80% rule” where you just keep the ones that explain greater than 80% of the variance, but this is obviously not a very rigorous cutoff. Another is more mathematically subtle, which begins with calculating the eigenvalues of the dataset.

eigenvalues = pca$sdev^2

plot(c(1:12), eigenvalues, xlab = 'Principal Components', ylab = 'eigenvalue', las = 1)

The eigenvalues are proportional to the square of the ‘standard deviation’ output of prcomp. The “Kaiser-Guttman” criterion for retaining principal components states that you only keep the ones whose eigenvalues are greater than the average eigenvalue.

which(eigenvalues > mean(eigenvalues))
## [1] 1 2

By this criterion, (and the 80% rule), we only need to consider PC1 and PC2 for this particular dataset.

PCA on the whole dataset.

I limited the analysis above to the top 1000 most variable regions because I expect around this many regions to have significant differences in the dataset. The ‘less variable’ regions are variable for reasons that likely reflect additional biological and technical influences that we are less interested in. Let’s do this on the whole dataset (not filtering by 1000 most variable peaks), and see how this affects our conclusions from above:

pca2 = prcomp(t(scaled)) # only difference is that we don't filter. Otherwise the same data.

percentVar2 = round(100 * summary(pca2)$importance[2,])
cumuVar2 = round(100 * summary(pca2)$importance[3,])

prTab2 = data.frame(pca2$x, tcoldata)

prTab2 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(PC1, PC2, color = genotype, shape = sex)) +
  geom_point(size = 3, alpha = 0.5) + 
  xlab(paste0("PC1: ", percentVar2[1], "% variance")) + ylab(paste0("PC2: ", percentVar2[2], "% variance")) + 
  scale_color_manual(values = c("tomato", "blue")) + theme(axis.line = element_line(color = "black")) + 
  theme_bw() +  
  coord_fixed() +
  labs(title = 'Principal Component Analysis (all data)')

A ha. Our principal components still distinguish genotype and sex, but these components explain a smaller overall fraction of the variance. (just 45%). Let’s look at our barplot again:

b = barplot(percentVar2, horiz = FALSE, las = 1, ylab = 'Variance (%)', ylim = c(0,105))
lines(b, cumuVar2, type = 'b', col = 'red')

Definitely murkier. What does our statistical test tell us to retain?

eigenvalues2 = pca2$sdev^2

which(eigenvalues2 > mean(eigenvalues2))
## [1] 1 2 3

Despite this, our test now tells us to heed the third principal component as well. Let’s have a look at PC3…

prTab2 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(PC2, PC3, color = prepDate, shape = sex)) +
  geom_point(size = 3, alpha = 0.5) +

  theme_bw() +  
  coord_fixed() +
  labs(title = 'Principal Component Analysis (PC2 & 3, all data)')

Again, we don’t have any immediate thoughts about what the biological or technical explanations are for this principal component.

If we wanted to account for this source of variance in the model formula for DESeq2 analysis, we could determine groups on the basis of whether the value for PC3 is positive or negative, and include this in the design formula. We would have to add this to the object tcoldata.

tcoldata = cbind(tcoldata, PC3 = prTab2$PC3)

Then we could do DESeq2:

# initialize the DESeq dataset and process it:

tubdds = DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = tubcounts, colData = tcoldata, design = ~ PC3 + sex + genotype)
##   the design formula contains one or more numeric variables that have mean or
##   standard deviation larger than 5 (an arbitrary threshold to trigger this message).
##   Including numeric variables with large mean can induce collinearity with the intercept.
##   Users should center and scale numeric variables in the design to improve GLM convergence.
# now we perform DESeq
tubdds = DESeq(tubdds, parallel = FALSE)
## estimating size factors
## estimating dispersions
## gene-wise dispersion estimates
## mean-dispersion relationship
## final dispersion estimates
## fitting model and testing
resultsNames(tubdds)  # check the output of the comparisons made based on the design above.
## [1] "Intercept"               "PC3"                    
## [3] "sex_M_vs_F"              "genotype_tubopa_vs_wt13"
res.tub = results(tubdds, contrast = c("genotype", "tubopa", "wt13"), independentFiltering = FALSE)
res.tub = as.data.frame(res.tub)

We can now visualize how this affects our differential analysis:

MA Plot:

res.tub %>% 
  mutate(sig = padj < 0.05) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = log10(baseMean), y = log2FoldChange, color = sig)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.1) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(-5,5)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("TRUE" = "red", "FALSE" =  "black")) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = c(0,1,-1), linetype = 'dotted', color = 'blue') +
  theme_clean() +
  labs(title = "MA Plot",
       x = "log10(mean counts)",
       y = "log2(fold change) treatment/control")

Volcano:

supervolcano = res.tub %>% 
  mutate(sig = padj <= 0.05 & abs(log2FoldChange) >= 1) %>% 
  mutate(mean.intensity = baseMean/max(baseMean)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = log2FoldChange, y = -log10(padj), color = sig, size = mean.intensity)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.2) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim =c(-4,4)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = -log10(0.05), linetype = 'dashed', col = 'blue') +
  geom_vline(xintercept = log2(c(0.5,2)), linetype = 'dashed', col = 'blue') +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("TRUE" = 'red', "FALSE" = "black")) +
  theme_clean() +
  labs(title = 'volcano plot with mean intensity')

supervolcano+ 
  annotate(geom = "text", x = -3, y = 40, label = length(which(res.tub$padj <= 0.05 & res.tub$log2FoldChange <= -1))) + 
  annotate(geom = "text", x = 3, y = 40, label = length(which(res.tub$padj <= 0.05 & res.tub$log2FoldChange >= 1))) +
  annotate(geom = 'text', x = 0, y = 50, label = length(which(res.tub$padj <= 0.05 & abs(res.tub$log2FoldChange) < 1)))

Before when we didn’t consider the mysterious PC3, we had 136 ‘down’ peaks and ‘548’ up peaks. The middle was 1123 peaks. It appears, superficially, that including PC3 marginally affects the presumed true ‘up’ and ‘down’ peaks, and reduces substantially the ‘significant peaks with insufficient log2 fold change’. This appears to likely be an improvement in the analysis.
